<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-inverse-functions">
	<title>Inverse Functions</title>
	<!-- Exercises for Inverse Functions -->
				<exercises>
	<!-- Exercise 1 in OG Invere Functions -->
					<exercise>
							<statement>
									<p>
										The table below defines the function <m>m</m>. Is <m>m</m> an invertible function? Why or why not? If your answer is yes, construct a table-of-values for <m>m^{-1}</m>.
										<table>
	  <tabular halign="center" top="medium">
	    <row bottom="medium">
	      <cell left="medium" right="medium">
	        <m>x</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>1</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>2</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>3</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>4</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>5</m>
	      </cell>
	    </row>
	    <row bottom="medium">
	      <cell left="medium" right="medium">
	        <m>m(x)</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>0</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>5</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>10</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>15</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>20</m>
	      </cell>
	    </row>
	  </tabular>
	</table>
									</p>
							</statement>
							<solution>
								<p>
									<m>m</m> is an invertible function since it is one-to-one, i.e., each output corresponds to exactly one input. Below is a table-of-values for <m>m^{-1}</m>.
									<table>
	<tabular halign="center" top="medium">
		<row bottom="medium">
			<cell left="medium" right="medium">
				<m>x</m>
			</cell>
			<cell right="medium">
				<m>0</m>
			</cell>
			<cell right="medium">
				<m>5</m>
			</cell>
			<cell right="medium">
				<m>10</m>
			</cell>
			<cell right="medium">
				<m>15</m>
			</cell>
			<cell right="medium">
				<m>20</m>
			</cell>
		</row>
		<row bottom="medium">
			<cell left="medium" right="medium">
				<m>m^{-1}(x)</m>
			</cell>
			<cell right="medium">
				<m>1</m>
			</cell>
			<cell right="medium">
				<m>2</m>
			</cell>
			<cell right="medium">
				<m>3</m>
			</cell>
			<cell right="medium">
				<m>4</m>
			</cell>
			<cell right="medium">
				<m>5</m>
			</cell>
		</row>
	</tabular>
	</table>
								</p>
							</solution>
					</exercise>
	<!-- Exercise 2 in OG Invere Functions -->
					<exercise>
							<statement>
									<p>
										The table below defines the function <m>p</m>. Is <m>p</m> an invertible function? Why or why not? If your answer is yes, construct a table-of-values for <m>p^{-1}</m>.
										<table>
	  <tabular halign="center" top="medium">
	    <row bottom="medium">
	      <cell left="medium" right="medium">
	        <m>x</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>1</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>2</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>3</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>4</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>5</m>
	      </cell>
	    </row>
	    <row bottom="medium">
	      <cell left="medium" right="medium">
	        <m>p(x)</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>4</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>0</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>-2</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>0</m>
	      </cell>
	      <cell right="medium">
	        <m>2</m>
	      </cell>
	    </row>
	  </tabular>
	</table>
									</p>
							</statement>
							<solution>
								<m>p</m> isn't an invertible function since it isn't one-to-one. Notice how the output <m>0</m> corresponds to two distinct output values.
							</solution>
					</exercise>
				</exercises>
</section>
